verify_no_open_websocket_connections(zp)[source]¶

Validate that there are no open websocket connections remaining on a given player. Warnings are logged with the IP of the player and IP:PORT of the websocket client if an open connection is found.

Compares open connection to the known cloud connection source of ‘MuseCloudClient’ and do not count that as a reportable violation. This keeps us from logging warnings with empty data on tests that have players connected to the cloud.

webserver.muse_rest_commands module¶

class webserver.muse_rest_commands.MuseRestCommands[source]¶

Bases: webserver.base_muse_fixture.MuseRestClientFixtureMixin

Tests for RESTful Muse commands. These tests cover basic use cases to ensure all REST handlers in the player work and also SSL validations in the namespaces that require it. SWPBL-88608 removed the SSL requirement for some namespaces as captured in the table below.

Many tests in this suite are run as combinatorial cases to test both secure and insecure connections to the different namespaces. In those cases the Muse connection object is re-established within the test as the combinatorial vectors cannot be passed into setUpTest().

Namespace | SSL Required

favorites:1 | Yes groups:1 | Yes groupVolume:1 | No musicServiceAccounts:1 | Yes playback:1 | No playbackExtended:1 | Yes playbackMetadata:1 | No playbackSession:1 | Yes playerVolume:1 | No households:1 | Yes

# TODO: SWPBL-12525 add subscription command tests

See https://confluence.sonos.com/x/8FiwAw for documentation.

test_recoverable_error_counter_reset()[source]¶

Verifies player behavior to make sure the 503 retry counter is reset after a successful fetch

This test originally used Pause() commands to force the player to send out a version check request to the CQ /version endpoint. The bug fix for SWPBL-68185 tweaked the player enforcement of network calls when there isn’t enough playback data buffered such that these pauses caused this test to fail. This test now progresses naturally through the items in the CQ and runs reliably without the extra pauses.

See CL 295386 for all affected test changes based on this bugfix.

test_no_excessive_itemWindow_requests_in_window_edge()[source]¶

SWPBL-69512 This test mimics the alexa bridge. The window on the player does not have the final track but there is nothing to play beyond the initial window since we are forcing a 304 to that request.

Outline of Test Steps:
1. Add 15 tracks to queue (5 tracks ahead of default window size). The first track is a 10 second track, followed by 14 1-second tracks. 2. laodCloudQueue on the first track with playOnCompletion=true (no metadata) 3. Arm the error script to return 304 for all window requests. This means the player’s window won’t change throughout the course of the test. The window size should be 10. 4. Wait for the player to play to the end of the window.

The player should make one window fetch with reason=refresh for each track in the window edge (3 tracks - 7, 8, 9).

The player should make one window fetch with reason=queueCompleted at the end of the last track. :return:

test_playTTL_reset_by_ducking()[source]¶

SWPBL-88316 If a ducking command is received by a group, the PlayTTL should be reset to the initial value.

We only perform this test on non voice-capable devices. Voice-capable devices reset the playTTL internally and ignore muse ducking commands.

Test Steps:
  1. Load CQ with playTtlSec=5 and notifyUserIntent=True
  2. Play a track. Every ~2 seconds for ~10 seconds, issue a duck command - verify the player never stops playing.
  3. Wait ~5 seconds after we stop issuing ducking commands for the player to pause
  4. Verify the player pauses and sends a window request with reason=pausePlayTTLExpired
Returns:

webserver.test_ssdp_group_discovery module¶

This suite contains tests for the SSDP SpeakerGroup:1 Search Target (ST). The SSDP messages in this suite are parsed in /core/src/sonos/group_ssdp/notification.py where the correct ST is set in __init__(). All verifications within this script are comparing a device UDN from self.my_devices to the latest ‘alive’ or ‘byebye’ received with the SpeakerGroup:1 ST or NT.

Currently this script relies on the Workflow framework to manage the initial set of players to test against, which uses responses from the existing SSDP ST ZonePlayer:1 and then compares that to a list of M-Search responses returned for Speakergroup:1. This may be non-obvious to people not familiar with the framework and new search target and issues have been seen in the past where more devices were in self.my_devices than were returned by searching for SpeakerGroup:1 (this can be seen in some tests where we filter the SUB out of the my_devices list)
